title: SPI Subform 4
description: Safety Planning Intervention Subform 4 - Safety Planning Intervention

item.text:
Tip #1: Purpose
The purpose of collecting the suicidal crisis story is to understand how the crisis develops and identify points where other choices could be made to lessen risk.

Tip #2: Summary
Provide a summary of the specific crisis to communicate your understanding and support.

Tip #3: Interruptions
Let the client tell their story first with minimal interruption. Ask questions afterward if any details are missing.

Example dialogue
"Talking about your crisis will help us better understand what happened. We can then come up with ways to prevent such a distressing crisis from happening. If talking about your crisis is difficult, well work together to help you feel better, okay?"
Please tell me more about the last time you thought about or tried to end your life. Can you share a recent experience with me?

Tip #1
Identify a specific time the client thought about or tried to kill themself versus broad suicidal feelings by:
  •  Focusing on the specific suicidal crisis or events that were proximal to the crisis
  •  Asking for the date or the time when the crisis began and the location of the client during the crisis
  •  Keeping in mind that occasionally more distal events or risk factors may provide important contextual information
  •  Not focusing on a general discussion of the individuals history of suicide risk factors


    • Tip #2
    Identify and reflect to the client how their thoughts and feelings were different at each stage of a specific suicidal crisis.
1. Beginning of a specific suicidal crisis: How did you feel at that time? What was the reason for feeling this way?

3. Resolution of a specific suicidal crisis: How did the crisis become less intense?

Tip #1: Warning Signs
Help the client understand how recognizing warning signs provides an opportunity for them to use coping strategies or resources to lessen the suicide risk.

Tip #2: Suicide Risk Curve
Help the client understand how their personal suicidal crisis relates to the Suicide Risk Curve. Use the Curve to illustrate the severity of the crisis over time and where along the curve the Safety Plan should be used.

Tip #3: Purpose of Summary
The purpose of summarizing is to convey your empathy, understanding, and support while offering the client an opportunity to fill in any gaps about their crisis narrative.
Ask for permission to create a Safety Plan

Example dialogue
"Thank you for openly answering these questions. Talking about distress and thoughts about harming yourself can be difficult. Based on what you have shared, it sounds like you have [fill in suicidal ideation/attempt symptoms]. I would like to create a plan with you that will help keep you safe. What do you think about creating a plan together?"

Tip
If the client does not wish to make a Safety Plan at this time, empathetically explore the barriers and reasons for not wanting to create a plan. Share with the client that you will speak with a supervisor about next steps before getting back to them.
I would like to make a plan that will help you manage the suicidal crisis from becoming worse and help keep you safe. Would you like to create a plan together?
Discuss with your supervisor about the next steps to take.
Please describe next steps for the client

Tip
Introduce the Safety Plan as a personalized emergency plan that clearly describes the clients' warning signs, coping strategies, and resources they can use before or during a suicidal crisis. To create a plan that is specific and realistic for the client, remember to elicit feedback and identify solutions to potential barriers for each step of the plan.

Example dialogue #1
"Suicidal crises often come and go. If we put our heads together, I think there are things you could do to help de-escalate these crises. As I mentioned earlier, we can create a plan to help you stay safe. Its called a Safety Plan."

Example dialogue #2
"Other people who have had thoughts of harming themselves have found a Safety Plan to be very helpful."

I will start by telling you more about the Safety Plan and how to use it. A lot of times suicidal thoughts feel so overwhelming that we dont know what to do. If we put our heads together, we can build a plan that will help you recognize these thoughts before they become overwhelming and give you strategies to cope with the crisis. What are your thoughts so far?
Briefly introduce each step of the Safety Plan

Remind the client that if they try a step on this screen that does not work, they can skip ahead.

Warning Signs: These are the signs you notice that tell you a suicidal crisis may be starting.They are a reminder of when to pull out your Safety Plan.

Internal Coping Strategies: These are activities you can do on your own to help you feel better and distract yourself from suicidal thoughts. As time passes, these thoughts often become more manageable.

People and Social settings that provide Distraction: These are people or places you can go to distract yourself when you start feeling down. As time passes, suicidal thoughts often become more manageable.

Family Members or Friends Who May Offer Help: These are people you can talk to about your thoughts and feelings and who can support you during a crisis.

Professionals and professional services: These are trained mental health professionals or emergency services you can call if you need more help.

Making the Environment Safe: This involves removing or securing things around you that you might use to hurt yourself.

Tip: Definition of Warning Signs
Warning signs are the thoughts, feelings, or behaviors that you notice when you start to feel worse and might be at risk of hurting yourself.

Tip: Explain the Rationale
Help the client understand that recognizing warning signs and addressing the suicidal crisis before it fully escalates is one of the most effective ways of averting it. People often do not recognize a crisis is starting until they are already in the middle of it, which makes the crisis harder to manage.

Example dialogue #1
"The reason were identifying warning signs is to recognise the crisis before it starts: when you notice warning signs, thats when you pull out your Safety Plan."

Tip: Be Specific
Work with the client to identify specific (e.g., feeling physical pain in the chest) rather than vague (e.g., feeling ill) warning signs. Some examples of specific warning signs include:
  •  Thoughts:
    "Thinking about my wifes death and how I handled it"
  •  Behaviors:
    "Engaging in self-injury"
  •  Physical signs:
    "Feeling slowed down or numb"

Example dialogue #2
"How will you know when you are in crisis and that the Safety Plan should be used? What were the warning signs that you experienced during the crisis that you told me about?"
From your recent experience, what were the specific warning signs that will remind you to use your safety plan?
Use the following ideas to prompt the client if they cannot think of warning signs themselves.

•   Feeling hopeless
  •   Feeling empty
  •   Feeling lonely and alone
  •   Feeling that you failed
  •   Feeling guilty or ashamed
  •   Feeling useless/has no purpose
  •   Feeling angry and like nothing is going to change/get better

•   Pain
  •   Insomnia
  •   Increased sleep
  •   Lack of appetite
  •   Tiredness

Tip: Explain the Rationale
Distracting oneself helps lower risk by allowing the suicidal crisis to pass without acting on suicidal urges. As time passes, suicidal feelings often become more manageable.

Tip: Be Specific
Identifying specific coping strategies that are meaningful, enjoyable, soothing, offer hope, or serve as effective distractors. These strategies should be specific. For example, "taking a walk to the market" is better than "taking a walk."

Tip: Select Adaptive Strategies
Select adaptive distracting activities by checking if they are feasible. Do not endorse distracting activities that can increase suicide risk (e.g., having a few drinks).

Example dialogue #1
"What activities could you do by yourself to help take your mind off your problems even if it is for a brief period of time?"

Example dialogue #2
"How likely do you think you would be able to do this activity during a time of crisis? What might prevent you from thinking of this activity or doing this activity even after you think of it?"
Things I can do on my own to distract and keep myself safe:
Possible ideas for discussion if the client cannot come up with ideas themselves

•   Watching TV
  •   Listening to music
  •   Using social media

•   Walking
  •   Walking in the park
  •   Exercising
  •   Going to the gym
  •   Playing sports
  •   Gardening
  •   Meditating

•   Playing video games
  •   Reading
  •   Cooking
  •   Painting
  •   Crafting
  •   Cleaning

Step 3
People and social settings that provide distraction

Tip: Explain the Rationale
"These are the people or places you can go to to distract yourself when you start feeling down. This will help take your mind off of the crisis, and give time for the suicidal thoughts to go down."

Tip: Be Specific
Identify pleasant and distracting social settings and family and friends that the client can engage with without explicitly informing them of their suicidal state. Identify:
  •  Specific places that are accessible, their location, directions, and hours of operation (if applicable)
  •  Social activities that do not require too much advanced planning
  •  Potential barriers

Tip: Identify Healthy Contacts and Places
Encourage healthy social contacts and exclude places where alcohol or substances are present, people who upset the client, and places that could increase suicide risk (e.g., having to walk past a tree that reminds the client of hanging).

Example dialogue #1
"Who can you contact or where can you go to help take your mind off your problems or help you feel better, even for a brief time? You dont need to tell these people that you are feeling suicidal. How likely do you think you would be able to reach out to this person or go to this place during a time of crisis? What might stop you? What could make it easier?"

Example dialogue #2
"If you cannot think of any people or social settings to put down on this step of your plan right now, thats okay. We can revisit this step later."
Specific people I can contact to take my mind off problems and feel better:
Specific social settings I can go to take my mind off problems and feel better:
Places, groups, social media, or events

Step 4
Family members or friends who may offer help

Tip: Explain the Rationale
"Connecting with family or friends who care about us and are readily available to provide support may help you feel better."

Tip: Assess Support
If the client says that they have no social support, carefully and sensitively assess whether they actually have no support or if they are perceiving barriers to reaching out to the supports in their lives.

Tip: Encourage Sharing
Encourage the client to share their plan by:
  •  Identifying family or friends who can use the Safety Plan to help the client. Those people should have a copy of the plan and understand their roles in advance.
  •  Include names and phone numbers directly in the plan.

Example dialogue
"Among your family or friends, who do you think you could contact for help and talk to during a crisis? What are the barriers to contacting this person? How would you overcome them?"
People who are available and can provide support during a crisis:
Problem solve barriers to seeking help
Are you willing to share your plan with this person?

Step 5
Professionals or professional services that can help during a crisis

Tip: Explain the Rationale
"If your suicidal thoughts do not go down, these professionals or professional services are trained to help during a suicidal crisis or emergency."

Tip: Address Reluctance
The client may be reluctant to contact professionals and disclose suicidal thoughts for fear of being hospitalized. For this concern, it may be helpful to describe a range of interventions or services that could be offered when reaching out for help, with hospitalization being only one type of care that may be offered.

Example dialogue
"Who are the mental health professionals or agencies that should be included in your plan? What is the likelihood that you would contact them? What could prevent you from doing so?"

The suicide and crisis lifeline number is 988. This number is available 24/7 in English and Spanish and offers free and confidential support via calling and texting.
Additional hotline numbers you can contact:

item.text: This screen is for providers to view only. Do not show it to the client.

Tip: Explain the Rationale
"Making the environment safe by reducing your access to lethal means allows the suicidal urge to decrease as time passes. The more time passes without coming into close contact with a lethal method, the less likely you are to act on your thoughts and the more likely they are to diminish and become more manageable."

Tip: Ask about Pills and Firearms
Always ask the client about taking pills or using a firearm. Do not share other methods on the screen, unless the client has mentioned a history with that method.

Tip: Explore Concerns
If faced with reluctance when discussing lethal means, explore the concerns by:
  •  Reassuring the client that reducing access to means is highly effective at preventing suicide as it gives the client time to calm down, apply the steps in their Safety Plan, and let the urge pass
  •  Being sensitive and collaborative
  •  Reinforcing that removing or reducing access to dangerous items will not last forever
  •  Asking the client to list the pros and cons of having access to each lethal method

Example dialogue #1
"[If person has not talked about methods of suicide] When you are thinking of suicide, have you thought of ways to kill yourself? Do you have access or could you get access to [insert means] if you wanted to?".

Example dialogue #2
"[If person has attempted suicide or has discussed means] You mentioned earlier that you have tried to kill yourself or thought about killing yourself by [insert means]. Have you thought about other ways to kill yourself? Do you have access to or could you get access to [insert means] if you wanted to?"
The methods I have thought about using include:

valueCoding.display: Going in front of a moving vehicle

item.text:
Tip
While removing very dangerous items from the home is often the safest avenue, you should collaboratively decide with your client on a plan that prioritizes safety while still being feasible. Sometimes, coming up with a slightly less safe plan that the client will actually complete is preferable to a very safe plan that will never be realized (e.g., removing all the knives from home may be safer, but giving them to a family member to hold on to is much more feasible).

Example dialogue
"What can we do to make the environment safer?"
These are the specific ways I can make my environment safer by reducing access to a lethal method:
Taking pills - I will protect myself from this risk by:
Using a firearm - I will protect myself from this risk by:
Going in front of a moving vehicle - I will protect myself from this risk by:
Cutting - I will protect myself from this risk by:
Hanging - I will protect myself from this risk by:
Jumping - I will protect myself from this risk by:
Drowning - I will protect myself from this risk by:
Other ways I will make my environment safer:

Tip
Review the entire plan with the client and discuss how to use it: "When you feel a suicidal crisis arising, go through each step of your plan, starting with recognizing warning signs and trying internal coping strategies. If a step works, you can stop there. If a step does not help you feel better, please try the next step on the plan. You can also skip to the step that you think will help the most with the crisis, and remember that you do not need to follow all the steps before asking for help. If you feel like you are not able to keep yourself safe, please contact emergency services."

Example dialogue:
"How likely is it that you will use the plan? What could keep you from using it when you start to feel suicidal? How can you remind yourself the importance of using the plan if you forget or dont feel like it?"
From your recent experience, what were the specific warning signs that will remind you to use your safety plan?

Explain how to use the Safety Plan and provide the client with a copy

Tip #1
Provide a copy of the Safety Plan at the end of the session:
  •  Check that the client understands each step
  •  Encourage them to share a copy of the plan with their friends and family listed on it

Tip #2
Discuss a location to store the Safety Plan:
  •  Agree on a readily accessible location
  •  Consider placing copies in important locations to serve as reminders (e.g., where lethal means are stored)
  •  Consider attaching a reminder of reasons for living (e.g., pictures of their children or loved ones)

When you feel a suicidal crisis arising, go through each step of your plan. If a step works, you can stop there. If a step doesn't work, try the next step on the plan. You can also skip to the step that you think will help the most with the crisis, and remember that you do not need to follow all the steps before asking for help. If you feel like you are not able to keep yourself safe, please contact emergency services.

I will share a copy of your plan at the end of our session today. You can also provide a copy to the family and friends you identified in Step 4 that can help you during a suicidal crisis. Do you have any questions?
If anything changes about the client's situation or you have any questions in between the follow-up meetings, please speak with a local clinical supervisor.

In a few days, I would like to meet for a follow-up. The purpose of this meeting is for us to review your Safety Plan together. We will check in on how you are doing and revise your plan based on what is and is not working. Do you have any questions? Let's schedule this meeting now:
